04312nam a22005295i 9780226139500DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802261395007 a10.7208/97802261395002doi  a(DE-B1597)524775  a(OCoLC)781254552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ175.32.R45 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a501a501a5091 aDear, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Intelligibility of Nature :bHow Science Makes Sense of the World /cPeter Dear. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (254 p.) :b6 halftones, 20 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ascience.culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Science as Natural Philosophy, Science as Instrumentality -- t1. The Mechanical Universe from Galileo to Newton -- t2. A Place for Everything: The Classification of the World -- t3. The Chemical Revolution Thwarted by Atoms -- t4. Design and Disorder: The Origin of Species -- t5. Dynamical Explanation: The Aether and Victorian Machines -- t6. How to Understand Nature? Einstein, Bohr, and the Quantum Universe -- tConclusion: Making Sense in Science -- tNotes -- tBibliographical Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout the history of the Western world, science has possessed an extraordinary amount of authority and prestige. And while its pedestal has been jostled by numerous evolutions and revolutions, science has always managed to maintain its stronghold as the knowing enterprise that explains how the natural world works: we treat such legendary scientists as Galileo, Newton, Darwin, and Einstein with admiration and reverence because they offer profound and sustaining insight into the meaning of the universe. In The Intelligibility of Nature, Peter Dear considers how science as such has evolved and how it has marshaled itself to make sense of the world. His intellectual journey begins with a crucial observation: that the enterprise of science is, and has been, directed toward two distinct but frequently conflated ends—doing and knowing. The ancient Greeks developed this distinction of value between craft on the one hand and understanding on the other, and according to Dear, that distinction has survived to shape attitudes toward science ever since. Teasing out this tension between doing and knowing during key episodes in the history of science—mechanical philosophy and Newtonian gravitation, elective affinities and the chemical revolution, enlightened natural history and taxonomy, evolutionary biology, the dynamical theory of electromagnetism, and quantum theory—Dear reveals how the two principles became formalized into a single enterprise, science, that would be carried out by a new kind of person, the scientist. Finely nuanced and elegantly conceived, The Intelligibility of Nature will be essential reading for aficionados and historians of science alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy of nature. 0aReasoning. 0aScience. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226139500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226139500.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles